1.translation-en: Where are the two men going?

2.translation-en: The two of them are going for meat.

notes: Note order -possibly focus first, then pronoun either side of the verb (keep the verbs together? or post-verbal topic?
example - response to basic introduction question

7.full_text: mithi baduani ini/ bakarranyi marnngarra yundru
7.translation-en: You have the ability to make a boomerang.
notes: Another example where the focus is first, then the verb, then the pronoun (maybe the focus is "make a boomerang"?)
Nice! Nominative on a nominalized verb
Imperative verb going first. Not sure if all examples like that - check.

10.full_text: murra nganytya gakudya marnngarra ingka bakarranyi
10.translation-en: OK, my uncle will make you a boomerang.
notes: mura - better translation might be OK or "well" rather than "finished" based on examples like this.

11.translation-en: I am not able to make a boomerang.
notes: Maybe literal trans is "no, I'm unable to make"

13.translation-en: The kids are all swimming in the water.

15.translation-en: I think I'll lie down here in the shade.

18.translation-en: A man (that one) is lying in the shade.

19.translation-en: (It's?) late, I will lie down, I think.

21.full_text: wina ngali barnrdirra winawarra ngali gulharra wiyilya
21.translation-en: We will sit down close to the fire. [We will move close to sit close to the fire.]

22.full_text: dhilagala nhaniguru dhila bari/ gurru nhanha ngalingu gulparra
22.translation-en: This cold wind is blowing, the two of us will build a windbreak.

23.translation-en: I think we will light a fire.

notes: Check on -gali vs -nga for past tense.

27.translation-en: He fell down and hurt his leg.
notes: Note relative order of -wa and past tense marker.
sure that the -na here is really accusative and shouldn't be a nominative instead?

28.full_text: mirlaani maltya galgurrigala/ ngalingu ngurra galirra nhungala
28.translation-en: The sun is going down - late. The two of us make camp over here.
notes: maltya late adverb or adjective? any additional examples?

29.full_text: nhungalaguru bari ngalingu ngurra galirra burngalunga
29.translation-en: I think the two of us will make camp over there at the gum tree.
notes: -guru should have a suffix marker I think

30.translation-en: I think the two of us will sleep here.

31.full_text: wikarla mirla warlpalha ngali yanhthabarra ngali yanhthabarra
31.translation-en: Tomorrow when the sun comes up the two of us will go on.
notes: ba as "away" vs ba as emphatic?
several other instances of ba + -ra (future) are glossed as EMPH, not 'away'

32.translation-en: Tomorrow the two of us will go a long way.

34.translation-en: The day after tomorrow stay - (then?) you will go away.

35.translation-en: Hey, this is my meat here.

36.full_text: walya ingka nhaniguru nguthiani/ ngutyadhikarra nganha
36.translation-en: This is not your meat, give it back to me.

37.full_text: murra ngathu inha ngutyadhikarra/ ingka nguthiani
37.translation-en: OK, I will give you back your meat. [Finished, I will give it back to you / It is your meat.]

38.translation-en: I thought this meat here was mine.

39.translation-en: Don't pick up this man's stick. (It is) this man's.

43.translation-en: I am not able to lift up this stone.

46.full_text: ga ngathu nhanhaguru warlpabarra bilkaanha ingka
46.translation-en: Yes, I will lift this log for you.

47.translation-en: Come, the two of us will cross to the other side.

48.translation-en: This water is not crossable. It is deep. [Cannot cross the water, deep.]

50.full_text: dhuna-bari ngali wirarra burlilha nhanigurru ngakaani
50.translation-en: The two of us will wait until the water falls. [The two of us will wait, the water will fall.]

notes: example - another one with no copula

56.translation-en: I will return the day after tomorrow.

57.translation-en: When will the two of you return?

58.translation-en: The two of us will return the day after tomorrow.

59.translation-en: He will return the day after tomorrow.

60.translation-en: Come, the two of us will go.

61.translation-en: Look at the snake on the stone. [Look at it / The snake is on the stone.]

62.translation-en: Where is the snake? I don't see (it).

63.translation-en: That one on the stone by the gum tree.

64.full_text: ga murra ngathu nhadyagala nhanhagurru murnaanha
64.translation-en: Yes, OK, I see the snake.
